06638nam a22007575i 9780822383482DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223834827 a10.1515/97808223834822doi  a(DE-B1597)552145  a(OCoLC)1058874706  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aJC330.2b.E74 2002 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a305.822100aEthnography in Unstable Places :bEveryday Lives in Contexts of Dramatic Political Change /cElizabeth Mertz, Kay B. Warren, Carol J. Greenhouse. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (446 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Altered States, Altered Lives -- tPart One. Law against Culture -- tGhettos in the Holocaust: The Improvisation of Social Order in a Culture of Terror -- tUnsettled Settlers: Internal Pacification and Vagrancy in Namibia -- tJudges without Courts: The Legal Culture of German Reunification -- tPart Two. Ethnographies of Agency in the Fissures of the State -- tEthnography in/of Transnational Processes: Following Gyres in the Worlds of Big Science and European Integration -- tThe Composite State: The Poor and the Nation in Manila -- tDomestic Matters: Feminism and Activism among Palestinian Women in Israel -- t''Best Interests'' and the Repatriation of Vietnamese Unaccompanied Minors -- tPart Three. Resistance and Remembrance -- tBeating the Bounds: Law, Identity, and Territory in the New Europe -- t''Honest Bandits'' and ''Warped People'': Russian Narratives about Money, Corruption, and Moral Decay -- tTrance against the State -- tPart Four. Conclusion -- tThe Perfidy of Gaze and the Pain of Uncertainty: Anthropological Theory and the Search for Closure -- tToward an Anthropology of Fragments, Instabilities, and Incomplete Transitions -- tContributors -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEthnography in Unstable Places is a collection of ethnographic accounts of everyday situations in places undergoing dramatic political transformation. Offering vivid case studies that range from the Middle East and Africa to Europe, Russia, and Southeast Asia, the contributing anthropologists narrate particular circumstances of social and political transformation-in contexts of colonialism, war and its aftermath, social movements, and post-Cold War climates-from the standpoints of ordinary people caught up in and having to cope with the collapse or reconfiguration of the states in which they live.Using grounded ethnographic detail to explore the challenges to the anthropological imagination that are posed by modern uncertainties, the contributors confront the ambiguities and paradoxes that exist across the spectrum of human cultures and geographies. The collection is framed by introductory and concluding chapters that highlight different dimensions of the book's interrelated themes-agency and ethnographic reflexivity, identity and ethics, and the inseparability of political economy and interpretivism.Ethnography in Unstable Places will interest students and specialists in social anthropology, sociology, political science, international relations, and cultural studies.Contributors. Eve Darian-Smith, Howard J. De Nike, Elizabeth Faier, James M. Freeman, Robert T. Gordon, Carol J. Greenhouse, Nguyen Dinh Huu, Carroll McC. Lewin, Elizabeth Mertz, Philip C. Parnell, Nancy Ries, Judy Rosenthal, Kay B. Warren, Stacia E. Zabusky  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPolitical stabilityxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aSocial structurexPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aGreenhouse, Carol J., econtributor.4ctb4htt